[{"sha":"0d9b0ed678e2b106e769e974f13aaf100e46351c","author":{"name":"Drew Erny","email":"db55f14336294d3287c922ab67a84bd4af5a0c81@mirantis.com"},"message":"Fix possible overlapping IPs

A node is no longer using its load balancer IP address when it no longer
has tasks that use the network that requires that load balancer. When
this occurs, the swarmkit manager will free that IP in IPAM, and may
reaassign it.

When a task shuts down cleanly, it attempts removal of the networks it
uses, and if it is the last task using those networks, this removal
succeeds, and the load balancer IP is freed.

However, this behavior is absent if the container fails. Removal of the
networks is never attempted.

To address this issue, I amend the executor. Whenever a node load
balancer IP is removed or changed, that information is passedd to the
executor by way of the Configure method. By keeping track of the set of
node NetworkAttachments from the previous call to Configure, we can
determine which, if any, have been removed or changed.

At first, this seems to create a race, by which a task can be attempting
to start and the network is removed right out from under it. However,
this is already addressed in the controller. The controller will attempt
to recreate missing networks before starting a task.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Kostadin Plachkov <k.n.plachkov@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aiordache/moby/commits/cd40eb89aea1d5f4fdfe0b0baa5b37ac513f5f75"},{"sha":"0d9b0ed678e2b106e769e974f13aaf100e46351c","author":{"name":"Drew Erny","email":"db55f14336294d3287c922ab67a84bd4af5a0c81@mirantis.com"},"message":"Fix possible overlapping IPs

A node is no longer using its load balancer IP address when it no longer
has tasks that use the network that requires that load balancer. When
this occurs, the swarmkit manager will free that IP in IPAM, and may
reaassign it.

When a task shuts down cleanly, it attempts removal of the networks it
uses, and if it is the last task using those networks, this removal
succeeds, and the load balancer IP is freed.

However, this behavior is absent if the container fails. Removal of the
networks is never attempted.

To address this issue, I amend the executor. Whenever a node load
balancer IP is removed or changed, that information is passedd to the
executor by way of the Configure method. By keeping track of the set of
node NetworkAttachments from the previous call to Configure, we can
determine which, if any, have been removed or changed.

At first, this seems to create a race, by which a task can be attempting
to start and the network is removed right out from under it. However,
this is already addressed in the controller. The controller will attempt
to recreate missing networks before starting a task.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/aiordache/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

[{"sha":"e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) supported versions fix (#2193)

As we were using caret ranges `^` instead of tilde ranges `~`
to catch the latest versions (1.1.0, 1.2.0) both of them could
catch the 1.2.0 version. Versions are delivered to our gui
as a hashmap, and when gui on the 1.2.0 version was asking our api
for the supported version of envoy it could receive the response
from range `^1.2.0` and then, everything was fine, and sometimes
it could receive a response from the `^1.1.0` range, and then
it was displaying warning.

It was happening because in the gui, we are iterating over
the hashmap with versions, and there is no consistency in
the order of keys (which is normal).

Also added tests to make sure there is always only one constraint

[{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

[{"sha":"e83ad981361656736ad508c948331cc179480ecf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e83ad981361656736ad508c948331cc179480ecf"}]

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

On Linux/Unix it was just a thin wrapper for unix.Unmount(), and a no-op on Windows.

This function was not used anywhere (also not externally), so removing this without
deprecating first.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dgkh1975/moby/commits/26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b"},{"sha":"46c591b045a77b7f0f96f96a51d8304264685929","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: deprecate some consts and move them to pkg/idtools

These consts were used in combination with idtools utilities, which
makes it a more logical location for these consts to live.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380711604
Change-Id: If8edc9e9bc915eab5a0285a6502a7bf56c6ed10a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/27c5fa686e0f519e066b6da5118871ab4cb805f7"},{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

[{"sha":"c38eabe88a489c33acf51c1fd473afa45f8025b5","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/c38eabe88a489c33acf51c1fd473afa45f8025b5"}]

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vsimon/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"e417d796a0dc4c7206abeefd6c29ab615da9470f","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"don't add duplicate proxy provider nodes

[{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdavalon01/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

On Linux/Unix it was just a thin wrapper for unix.Unmount(), and a no-op on Windows.

This function was not used anywhere (also not externally), so removing this without
deprecating first.

[{"sha":"7c97896747726554165480d102d9e46c54334cba","author":{"name":"Steffen Butzer","email":"46adcc64d578e77abc0454761760af40d6d6f8c9@outlook.com"},"message":"libnetwork: processEndpointDelete: Fix deadlock between getSvcRecords and processEndpointDelete

We had some hosts with quite a bit of cycling containers that ocassionally causes docker daemons to lock up.
Most prominently `docker run` commands do not respond and nothing happens anymore.

Looking at the stack trace the following is at least likely sometimes a cause to that:
Two goroutines g0 and g1 can race against each other:
* (g0) 1. getSvcRecords is called and calls (*network).Lock()
       --> Network is locked.
* (g1) 2. processEndpointDelete is called, and calls (*controller).Lock()
       --> Controller is locked
* (g1) 3. processEndpointDelete tries (*network).ID() which calls (*network).Lock().
* (g0) 4. getSvcRecords calls (*controller).Lock().

3./4. are deadlocked against each other since the other goroutine holds the lock they need.

References https://github.com/moby/libnetwork/blob/b5dc37037049d9b9ef68a3c4611e5eb1b35dd2af/network.go

Signed-off-by: Steffen Butzer <steffen.butzer@outlook.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/steffengy/moby/commits/7c97896747726554165480d102d9e46c54334cba"}]

[{"sha":"e5942f576d5e1281ad64ab26672020a502fce780","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/e5942f576d5e1281ad64ab26672020a502fce780"}]

[{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

On Linux/Unix it was just a thin wrapper for unix.Unmount(), and a no-op on Windows.

This function was not used anywhere (also not externally), so removing this without
deprecating first.

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

deprecating first.

[{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/kuma/commits/ec83eee3dbf11f1453f5db61685533489dc24e77"},{"sha":"e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) supported versions fix (#2193)

As we were using caret ranges `^` instead of tilde ranges `~`
to catch the latest versions (1.1.0, 1.2.0) both of them could
catch the 1.2.0 version. Versions are delivered to our gui
as a hashmap, and when gui on the 1.2.0 version was asking our api
for the supported version of envoy it could receive the response
from range `^1.2.0` and then, everything was fine, and sometimes
it could receive a response from the `^1.1.0` range, and then
it was displaying warning.

It was happening because in the gui, we are iterating over
the hashmap with versions, and there is no consistency in
the order of keys (which is normal).

Also added tests to make sure there is always only one constraint
per version, to not allow similar situation to happen again.

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

On Linux/Unix it was just a thin wrapper for unix.Unmount(), and a no-op on Windows.

This function was not used anywhere (also not externally), so removing this without
deprecating first.

[{"sha":"25dfbbd30d748ed29f3841273fa7208e4184c300","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/25dfbbd30d748ed29f3841273fa7208e4184c300"}]

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

On Linux/Unix it was just a thin wrapper for unix.Unmount(), and a no-op on Windows.

This function was not used anywhere (also not externally), so removing this without
deprecating first.

* Move act related stuff out of EventInternals","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017"},{"sha":"7641eec043961012f6238feaa9b47bc987ea9a0d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/7641eec043961012f6238feaa9b47bc987ea9a0d"}]

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests

[{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"}]

[{"sha":"a945b379d8572810536119de360b53b949cbe4a7","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Explicit examples of -var escaping in various shells

The -var command line option comes with the disadvantage that a user must
contend both with Terraform's own parser and with the parser in whichever
shell they've decided to use, and different shells on different platforms
have different rules.

Previously we've largely just assumed that folks know the appropriate
syntax for the shell they chose, but it seems that command lines involving
spaces and other special characters arise rarely enough in other commands
that Terraform is often the first time someone needs to learn the
appropriate syntax for their shell.

We can't possibly capture all of the details of all shells in our docs,
because that's far outside of our own scope, but hopefully this new
section will go some way to give some real examples that will help folks
figure out how to write suitable escape sequences, if they choose to
set complex variable values on the command line rather than in .tfvars
as we recommend elsewhere on this page.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/a945b379d8572810536119de360b53b949cbe4a7"}]

[{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"2c9c756ab7e21903b284bd90687fcc55a9f8a93d","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Move internal version of act to shared module

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380632091
Change-Id: Ib18ec52fd24d60ef0f70c77b699f8023e37a0462","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/05963359f16c63a95fe5c08aa76bdef4094ab443"},{"sha":"9ee406469e4276c2d0bd5326a6290526ed485c1b","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Make TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass less conservative

Now TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass can merge resource reads and assigns with
TPUExecute when there are non-interfering resource accesses between read/assigns
and TPUExecute. Interference is checked with resource alias analysis, and now
the pass is a module pass.
Previously, the pass was too conservative and considered any resource access as
potentially interfering so in many valid cases we couldn't merge.
Also added tests, made terminology more consistent, and added debug messages.

Change-Id: I51ae2adcaefbc94a139eac4a5cafb5df724cb280","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/paolodedios/tensorflow/commits/491ea166528922468d5b5b7b826f42df44e3b88f"},{"sha":"4878ad9bb9a33637e62e340040b7bb0ed4506e4f","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data] Improve error message when dataset serialization fails.

Previously we would get an error along the lines of

NotFoundError: Resource localhost/hash_table_6d5754e2-c5bd-4c7f-8f99-5aa8782dd5a8/ResourceBase does not exist.

Now the error looks like

FailedPreconditionError: Serialization error while trying to register a dataset with tf.data service. The dataset may depend on a resource located on a different device. To address this, call `register_dataset` from the device with the resource, then use `from_dataset_id` to create per-device datasets. Original error: Invalid argument: Trying to access resource hash_table_8945247c-dee3-4c71-a49b-1d9d8aa5f13c located in device /job:localhost/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:0 from device /job:localhost/replica:0/task:0/device:CPU:1

To get the information about which device the resource is being accessed from, this CL plumbs the OpKernelContext through the SerializationContext.

[{"sha":"c1c363937b820283feef490ebed4253c1cd01eee","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Explicit examples of -var escaping in various shells

The -var command line option comes with the disadvantage that a user must
contend both with Terraform's own parser and with the parser in whichever
shell they've decided to use, and different shells on different platforms
have different rules.

Previously we've largely just assumed that folks know the appropriate
syntax for the shell they chose, but it seems that command lines involving
spaces and other special characters arise rarely enough in other commands
that Terraform is often the first time someone needs to learn the
appropriate syntax for their shell.

We can't possibly capture all of the details of all shells in our docs,
because that's far outside of our own scope, but hopefully this new
section will go some way to give some real examples that will help folks
figure out how to write suitable escape sequences, if they choose to
set complex variable values on the command line rather than in .tfvars
as we recommend elsewhere on this page.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/c1c363937b820283feef490ebed4253c1cd01eee"}]

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jpeach/kuma/commits/ec83eee3dbf11f1453f5db61685533489dc24e77"},{"sha":"e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) supported versions fix (#2193)

As we were using caret ranges `^` instead of tilde ranges `~`
to catch the latest versions (1.1.0, 1.2.0) both of them could
catch the 1.2.0 version. Versions are delivered to our gui
as a hashmap, and when gui on the 1.2.0 version was asking our api
for the supported version of envoy it could receive the response
from range `^1.2.0` and then, everything was fine, and sometimes
it could receive a response from the `^1.1.0` range, and then
it was displaying warning.

It was happening because in the gui, we are iterating over
the hashmap with versions, and there is no consistency in
the order of keys (which is normal).

Also added tests to make sure there is always only one constraint
per version, to not allow similar situation to happen again.

Signed-off-by: Bart Smykla <bartek@smykla.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jpeach/kuma/commits/e2bd183084de3871bfa737df15bb5d5014d22577"},{"sha":"0671510cc1c8f8dffea452e251dfd335a8da3932","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-dp) validate the DP proxy type

[{"sha":"422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Delete test-utils implementation of `act` (#21703)

* Delete test-utils implementation of `act`

Since it's dev-only now, we can use the one provided by the reconciler.

* Move act related stuff out of EventInternals","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017"},{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

* Move internal version of act to shared module

No reason to have three different copies of this anymore.

I've left the the renderer-specific `act` entry points because legacy
mode tests need to also be wrapped in `batchedUpdates`. Next, I'll update
the tests to use `batchedUpdates` manually when needed.

* Migrates tests to use internal module directly

Instead of the `unstable_concurrentAct` exports. Now we can drop those
from the public builds.

I put it in the jest-react package since that's where we put our other
testing utilities (like `toFlushAndYield`). Not so much so it can be
consumed publicly (nobody uses that package except us), but so it works
with our build tests.

* Remove unused internal fields

These were used by the old act implementation. No longer needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16"}]

* Move act related stuff out of EventInternals","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017"},{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

* Move internal version of act to shared module

No reason to have three different copies of this anymore.

I've left the the renderer-specific `act` entry points because legacy
mode tests need to also be wrapped in `batchedUpdates`. Next, I'll update
the tests to use `batchedUpdates` manually when needed.

* Migrates tests to use internal module directly

Instead of the `unstable_concurrentAct` exports. Now we can drop those
from the public builds.

I put it in the jest-react package since that's where we put our other
testing utilities (like `toFlushAndYield`). Not so much so it can be
consumed publicly (nobody uses that package except us), but so it works
with our build tests.

* Remove unused internal fields

These were used by the old act implementation. No longer needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16"}]

(#1751)

This PR aims to avoid a potential deadlock that happens in a race condition when shutting down RoutingTableProvider.

The race condition happens when the RoutingTableProvider is shut down and the corresponding HelixManager is processing an onLiveInstanceChange event. Both threads require 2 locks, HelixManager lock and RoutingTableProvider._lastSeenSessions, in different orders.
To resolve this problem, this PR changes 2 logics.
1. Remove the _lastSeenSessions lock usage. So no more deadlock. The logic correctness is now ensured by the AtomicReference.getAndSet method.
2. Remove LiveInstanceChangeListener in the shutdown call before processing the other logics. This is a missing logic and should be done regardless of the deadlock problem.Moreover, this change also avoids a more complicated race condition introduced by the previous change that may lead to CurrentStates callback handler leakage.

Test cases in TestZkCallbackHandlerLeak has been updated to validate the logic changes.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/apache/helix/commits/faa0cd3fb38fb4e9ffb22969aed0f126f41964cb"},{"sha":"9b0d085fd039be4f096afdd79cf50e1b1e61e3d8","author":{"name":"Jiajun Wang","email":"9aafcb59640c5ea54c57c4c0f0b46ed999af8e22@linkedin.com"},"message":"Automatically create issues for the failed tests. * Delete test-utils implementation of `act`

Since it's dev-only now, we can use the one provided by the reconciler.

* Move act related stuff out of EventInternals","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017"},{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

* Move internal version of act to shared module

No reason to have three different copies of this anymore.

I've left the the renderer-specific `act` entry points because legacy
mode tests need to also be wrapped in `batchedUpdates`. Next, I'll update
the tests to use `batchedUpdates` manually when needed.

* Migrates tests to use internal module directly

Instead of the `unstable_concurrentAct` exports. Now we can drop those
from the public builds.

I put it in the jest-react package since that's where we put our other
testing utilities (like `toFlushAndYield`). Not so much so it can be
consumed publicly (nobody uses that package except us), but so it works
with our build tests.

* Remove unused internal fields

These were used by the old act implementation. No longer needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16"}]

Signed-off-by: Kostadin Plachkov <k.n.plachkov@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rvolosatovs/moby/commits/cd40eb89aea1d5f4fdfe0b0baa5b37ac513f5f75"},{"sha":"0d9b0ed678e2b106e769e974f13aaf100e46351c","author":{"name":"Drew Erny","email":"db55f14336294d3287c922ab67a84bd4af5a0c81@mirantis.com"},"message":"Fix possible overlapping IPs

A node is no longer using its load balancer IP address when it no longer
has tasks that use the network that requires that load balancer. When
this occurs, the swarmkit manager will free that IP in IPAM, and may
reaassign it.

When a task shuts down cleanly, it attempts removal of the networks it
uses, and if it is the last task using those networks, this removal
succeeds, and the load balancer IP is freed.

However, this behavior is absent if the container fails. Removal of the
networks is never attempted.

To address this issue, I amend the executor. Whenever a node load
balancer IP is removed or changed, that information is passedd to the
executor by way of the Configure method. By keeping track of the set of
node NetworkAttachments from the previous call to Configure, we can
determine which, if any, have been removed or changed.

At first, this seems to create a race, by which a task can be attempting
to start and the network is removed right out from under it. However,
this is already addressed in the controller. The controller will attempt
to recreate missing networks before starting a task.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rvolosatovs/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

[{"sha":"6988f786f125cbb01f2e3914b750eb08da484847","author":{"name":"Drew Erny","email":"db55f14336294d3287c922ab67a84bd4af5a0c81@mirantis.com"},"message":"vendor swarmkit to 2dcf70aafdc9ea55af3aaaeca440638cde0ecda6

Revendors swarmkit to fix a bug that could result in a mutex deadlock in
the logbroker.

Signed-off-by: Drew Erny <derny@mirantis.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/6988f786f125cbb01f2e3914b750eb08da484847"},{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43"},{"sha":"26f5db7a1da0223c7584492d6e9bdf1c7b81278b","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove unused system.Unmount() utility

On Linux/Unix it was just a thin wrapper for unix.Unmount(), and a no-op on Windows.

This function was not used anywhere (also not externally), so removing this without
deprecating first.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 380483654
Change-Id: Ie0abe0aa5cc6df86850f9ea035293f5d9c36d5ae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TEAdvanced/tensorflow/commits/636833c8ff5f716dfa2eddd60a9eae905d8f715a"},{"sha":"7c7c24704394eaf75553fb6622e60272ead9190a","author":{"name":"Taehee Jeong","email":"9658aeb0d6dabc12b71efd5872bbf9f3c41b726b@google.com"},"message":"Volatile requantize op should not be removed

RemoveVolatileOps pass accidentally deletes requantize op too, and the float op might get wrong quantized input.

Think about a graph:

```
Logistic ---> Div        -> ...
          |-> GatherNd   ---> Concat -> output
           (other input) -|
```

The scale from output is propagated back to Concat and GatherNd, but Logistic op has a fixed output scale and a requantize op should be there to correctly rescale quantized tensors. On the other hand, Div op is not quantizable and requires Q-DQ ops.

So after PrepareQuantize pass, the part of graph would look like:

```
Logistic -> Quantize -> Quantize(requantize) -> Dequantize ---> Div
                                 (volatile)                 |-> GatherNd
```

Then during Quantize pass, some Q/DQs are merged to form quantized ops.

```
Logistic(int8) -> Quantize(requantize) ---> Dequantize ---> Div
                           (volatile)   |-> GatherNd
```

The problem comes here when RemoveVolatileOps pass is called at the Dequantize op. With current logic, the graph would be like following and thus float Div op will emit error.

```
Logistic(int8) ---> Div (float)
                |-> Quantize(requantize) -> GatherNd
```

To resolve this, extra dequantized should not be removed when the quantize op is a requantize op.

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

[{"sha":"5f04517c483203e50e78b5d70d1c31cb0f912a43","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/system: remove deprecated GetOSVersion(), consts, SecurityInfo utils.

This removes the deprecated wrappers, so that the package no longer has
hcsshim as a dependency. These wrappers were no longer used in our code,
and were deprecated in the 20.10 release (giving external consumers to
replace the deprecated ones).

Note that there are two consts which were unused, but for which there is
no replacement in golang.org/x/sys;

    const (
        PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION = 0x00000080
        ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION       = 0x00000100
    )

PROCESS_TRUST_LABEL_SECURITY_INFORMATION is documented as "reserved", and I could
not find clear documentation about ACCESS_FILTER_SECURITY_INFORMATION, so not sure
if they must be included in golang.org/x/sys: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/openspecs/windows_protocols/ms-dtyp/23e75ca3-98fd-4396-84e5-86cd9d40d343

Since it's dev-only now, we can use the one provided by the reconciler.

* Move act related stuff out of EventInternals","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017"},{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

* Move internal version of act to shared module

No reason to have three different copies of this anymore.

I've left the the renderer-specific `act` entry points because legacy
mode tests need to also be wrapped in `batchedUpdates`. Next, I'll update
the tests to use `batchedUpdates` manually when needed.

* Migrates tests to use internal module directly

Instead of the `unstable_concurrentAct` exports. Now we can drop those
from the public builds.

I put it in the jest-react package since that's where we put our other
testing utilities (like `toFlushAndYield`). Not so much so it can be
consumed publicly (nobody uses that package except us), but so it works
with our build tests.

* Remove unused internal fields

These were used by the old act implementation. No longer needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16"}]

[{"sha":"422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Delete test-utils implementation of `act` (#21703)

* Delete test-utils implementation of `act`

Since it's dev-only now, we can use the one provided by the reconciler.

* Move act related stuff out of EventInternals","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/422e0bb3604dd7d3f6158df87b05932a43c89017"},{"sha":"06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"`act` should work without mock Scheduler (#21714)

Currently, in a React 18 root, `act` only works if you mock the
Scheduler package. This was because we didn't want to add additional
checks at runtime.

But now that the `act` testing API is dev-only, we can simplify its
implementation.

Now when an update is wrapped with `act`, React will bypass Scheduler
entirely and push its tasks onto a special internal queue. Then, when
the outermost `act` scope exists, we'll flush that queue.

I also removed the "wrong act" warning, because the plan is to move
`act` to an isomorphic entry point, simlar to `startTransition`. That's
not directly related to this PR, but I didn't want to bother
re-implementing that warning only to immediately remove it.

I'll add the isomorphic API in a follow up.

Note that the internal version of `act` that we use in our own tests
still depends on mocking the Scheduler package, because it needs to work
in production. I'm planning to move that implementation to a shared
(internal) module, too.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/06f7b4f43a93eae9111cfbd972ab1ae1148f6afb"},{"sha":"d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove internal `act` builds from public modules (#21721)

* Move internal version of act to shared module

No reason to have three different copies of this anymore.

I've left the the renderer-specific `act` entry points because legacy
mode tests need to also be wrapped in `batchedUpdates`. Next, I'll update
the tests to use `batchedUpdates` manually when needed.

* Migrates tests to use internal module directly

Instead of the `unstable_concurrentAct` exports. Now we can drop those
from the public builds.

I put it in the jest-react package since that's where we put our other
testing utilities (like `toFlushAndYield`). Not so much so it can be
consumed publicly (nobody uses that package except us), but so it works
with our build tests.

* Remove unused internal fields

These were used by the old act implementation. No longer needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/d7dce572c7453737a685e791e7afcbc7e2b2fe16"}]

* Schedule heartbeat on reply to avoid intensive throttling

According to a Chromium bug report, intensive throttling is not applied to timers that are scheduled from a "network response handler". This was in response to Chrome 88 breaking Microsoft SignalR in a similar way to what was reported in #4307.

I refactored our heartbeat based on their reference:
https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1186569#c3

* fix heartbeat timeout test

* simplify abnormalClose

* Update assets/js/phoenix.js
